## 1. One-Line Summary

- The Hook — A brutally demanding, high-ceiling powerhouse that rewards flawless technique and immense physical power with unmatched spin and lethal trajectory.
- Archetype — Uncompromising Aggressive Looper / Power Attacker

## 2. Performance Analysis

- Speed & Gears
    - Passive Block Speed: Relatively tame and highly controlled; the hard sponge does not activate easily on soft impact, preventing unwanted pop-ups.
    - Active Loop Speed: Explosive. When you possess the swing speed to engage the 43-degree (Butterfly scale) sponge, the top-end speed is blistering.
    - Linearity vs. Trampoline: Extremely linear. Unlike standard Tenergy 05, there is almost zero free trampoline effect. You get exactly what you put into the shot.
    - Mid-Distance Carry: Outstanding, but strictly dependent on the player's physical input. If you hit hard enough, the ball penetrates the court deeply with heavy momentum.

- Spin Generation
    - Top-End Spin: World-class. It boasts a higher spin ceiling than standard T05 because the harder sponge prevents the ball from bottoming out against the blade during maximum impact.
    - Opening Loop: Requires a very precise, fast brushing action. The sponge doesn't help lift the ball; your legs and wrist must do the work.
    - Serve Quality: Exceptional. The hard sponge allows for incredibly thin, sharp contact, generating massive backspin and sidespin without the ball bouncing off too quickly.

- Control & Short Game
    - Touch Play: Supremely precise. Pushes, drop shots, and stop-blocks are easier than with standard T05 because the rubber is less bouncy at low impacts.
    - Spin Sensitivity: Very high. The famous Code 05 topsheet bites everything, meaning incoming spin will affect your racket heavily if you don't actively counter-spin or adjust your angle.
    - Flick Window: Narrow. Strawberry and banana flicks require aggressive acceleration to avoid dumping the ball into the net.

- Throw Angle (Arc)
    - Trajectory: Medium-high. It is slightly lower than standard T05 because the ball doesn't sink as deeply into the sponge on average shots.
    - Arc Behavior: Very aggressive, dipping sharply at the very end of the flight path, making it extremely difficult for opponents to counter.

- Spin-Interaction Behavior
    - Against Heavy Topspin: Rock solid. It never folds or bottoms out, making it an ultimate weapon for high-level counter-looping.
    - Against Heavy Backspin: Demanding. Lifting heavy chop requires intense physical exertion and near-perfect form.
    - Error Pattern: When fatigued or out of position, players will typically miss into the net due to a lack of sponge activation.

## 3. Technique-by-Technique Breakdown

- Serve
    - Incredible grip allows for heavy spin on short serves. The lack of bounce keeps the ball low and tight to the net.

- Receive
    - Push/Stop: Fantastic control. The ball stays low, and you can easily keep the receive short.
    - Flick: Forehand flicks must be decisive and flat-hit or heavily brushed. Half-hearted flicks will fail.
    - Chiquita/Banana: Requires elite wrist speed. If executed correctly, it produces a devastatingly heavy topspin ball, but the margin for error is slim.

- Loop/Drive
    - First Loop (3rd Ball): Punishing if you have the footwork. If you are late, the rubber offers no forgiveness.
    - Continuous Looping: Excellent for high-energy rallies. The rubber thrives in topspin-to-topspin exchanges.
    - Power Loop / Kill: The absolute peak of this rubber's capability. Flawless energy transfer with zero energy loss.

- Countering
    - Counter-Topspin: One of the best rubbers on the market for this. The hard sponge dominates incoming spin.
    - Punch Counter / Active Block: Very stable, providing a direct, fast response without unwanted vibration.

- Blocking
    - Passive Block: Good control, deadens the ball nicely, though highly sensitive to the opponent's spin.
    - Active Block: Excellent. Pressing forward transfers energy beautifully, forcing the opponent back.

- Smash & Flat Hit
    - Surprisingly effective. The hard sponge provides a solid foundation for flat impacts, unlike softer, heavily tensioned rubbers that might feel mushy.

- Defense
    - Chop: Usable for desperation chops due to the hard sponge, but generally too fast and spin-sensitive for modern defenders.
    - Lob: Requires an active upward stroke. Passive lobs will fall short.

