## 6. Pros & Cons

- Pros
    - Unmatched top-end spin and power ceiling; it simply does not bottom out.
    - Exceptional short game and service control due to the lack of low-impact bounce.
    - Absolute stability in high-speed, heavy-spin counter-looping rallies.

- Cons
    - Zero forgiveness; highly demanding on footwork, positioning, and physical endurance.
    - Noticeably heavier than standard T05, which may affect blade balance.
    - Premium price point with a performance drop-off once the initial factory tension fades.

---

## 7. Recommended Users & Pairings

- Who Should Buy This: Elite amateurs (USATT 2100+), professional players, and hyper-aggressive loopers who physically overpower standard medium-hard rubbers.
- Who Should Avoid This: Beginners, intermediate players, players with compact/short strokes, and anyone seeking free speed or high forgiveness.
- Complementary Rubber Pairings (Opposite Side): Butterfly Tenergy 05, Dignics 80, or Tenergy 19 to provide a more forgiving, easier-to-activate backhand option.

---

## 8. Value & Alternatives

- Value Verdict: It is an expensive, elite-level tool. For the player who can harness it, it is worth every penny. For anyone else, it is a waste of money that will actively harm their development.
- Similar Alternatives
    - Same Brand: Butterfly Dignics 05 (slightly more forgiving, more grippy surface, longer durability but different sponge feel).
    - Rival Brand: Tibhar Evolution MX-K, Xiom Omega VII Tour, DHS Hurricane 3 Neo (National/Provincial 40+ degree, though DHS requires boosting for a similar feel).
- Closest Feel Match Summary: Plays like a hybrid between the raw grip/tension of standard T05 and the unyielding, rock-solid support of an unboosted Chinese tacky rubber.

